issue.title: Remove all leading $ not just one
issue.body:
Related to #996

This way we can give less fucks if we have more $

Before
```py
>>> "$ $ echo hello world".replace("$", "", 1).strip()
'$ echo hello world'
```
After
```py
>>> "$ $ echo hello world".lstrip("$ ")
'echo hello world'
```

% thefuck --version

issue.title: Git checkout should provide multiple corrections
issue.body:
When correcting git checkout, the default is to use the 'closest branch'.  We have a lot of branches with similar names, but quite often, what I actually meant to do was supply the '-b' flag.

Can the git checkout rule be updated to return all of the possible options, rather than trying to guess, based on some arbitrary priority?

issue.title: Receiving "command not found" on configuration
issue.body:
Tested in my shell on Xubuntu 14.04:

``` bash
♥ mhausman@Quasit:~ ‽ thefuck --alias
alias fuck='TF_CMD=$(TF_ALIAS=fuck PYTHONIOENCODING=utf-8 TF_SHELL_ALIASES=$(alias) thefuck $(fc -ln -1)) && eval $TF_CMD && history -s $TF_CMD'
♥ mhausman@Quasit:~ ‽ eval "$(thefuck --alias)"
: command not found
```

Note that it functions oddly afterwards. For instance, after running I did the following:

``` bash
♥ mhausman@Quasit:~ ‽ gdit
No command 'gdit' found, did you mean:
 Command 'dgit' from package 'dgit' (universe)
 Command 'git' from package 'git' (main)
 Command 'gedit' from package 'gedit' (main)
 Command 'gdis' from package 'gdis' (universe)
 Command 'edit' from package 'mime-support' (main)
gdit: command not found
♥ mhausman@Quasit:~ ‽ fuck
gedit [enter/↑/↓/ctrl+c]
```

It _looks_ like it's working. But when I hit enter, the command it actually ran was `gedit ^[[0m`. I'm not sure if that's related, but it seemed worth mentioning.
